Sentiment Analysis NLP Project! 📊😄😡¶

🌟 Objective & Overview:

Hi there, welcome! :) In my project, we're going to be focusing on building a deep learning-based Sentiment Analysis model using Keras! My main aim is to classify text into binary sentiments (‘positive’ or ‘negative’) by leveraging word embeddings, LSTM layers, and activation functions. Along the way, we will experiment with different activation functions and optimization techniques to evaluate their impact on performance!

Couple things about the dataset:

IMDB dataset having 50K movie reviews! This is a dataset for binary sentiment classification containing substantially more data than previous benchmark datasets.

  • a set of 25,000 highly polar movie reviews for training
  • a set of 25,000 for testing

Labels: Binary sentiments --> (Positive 😄 and Negative 😡)

Research Objectives:

  1. 💡 Data Preparation: Preprocess text data for tokenization and padding.

  2. 🎨 Model Development: Build an NLP model with three hidden layers using Embedding, LSTM, and Dense layers.

  3. 💨 Activation Function Experimentation: Test Sigmoid, Tanh, and ReLU.

  4. ⚙️ Optimization Analysis: Evaluate Adam and SGD optimizers.

  5. 📊 Evaluation: Analyze performance using metrics, confusion matrices, and classification reports.

import re 
# creating this function so we can remove unecessary HTML tags, change words to lowercase ... and other chrs!
def clean_text(text):
    text = re.sub(r'<.*?>', '', text)
    text = text.lower()
    text = re.sub(r'[^a-z\s]', '', text)
    return text

df['review'] = df['review'].apply(clean_text)

🌐 Model Design & Architecture Overview:¶

🔹 Our deep learning model uses:¶

  1. Embedding Layer: Transforms input tokens into dense vector representations.
  2. Bidirectional LSTM: Captures sequential relationships in text.
  3. Global Max Pooling: Reduces dimensionality efficiently.
  4. Dense Layers: Perform final classifications with varying activation functions.
In [27]:
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Embedding, Dense, Dropout

def create_model(activation_function='relu', optimizer='adam'):
    model = Sequential()
    
    model.add(Embedding(input_dim=5000, output_dim=64, input_length=100))
    
    model.add(Dense(128, activation=activation_function))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(Dense(64, activation=activation_function))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(Dense(32, activation=activation_function))

    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    return model

from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping

# now we are implementing early stopping to prevent any potential overfitting
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3, restore_best_weights=True)

# activation functions and optimizers to test!
activations = ['sigmoid', 'tanh', 'relu']
optimizer = 'adam'  

history_dict = {}
for activation in activations:
    print(f"\nTraining model with {activation} activation...")
    model = create_model(activation_function=activation, optimizer=optimizer)
    history = model.fit(
        X_train, y_train,
        validation_data=(X_val, y_val),
        epochs=10,
        batch_size=32,
        callbacks=[early_stopping],
        verbose=1
    )
    history_dict[activation] = history

🔍 Observations with the SGD Optimizer:¶

⚡ Sigmoid Activation:¶

  • 📉 Test Loss: Starts at 0.7016 but we can see that it does not improve significantly since it stagnates near 0.6930.
  • 📈 Test Accuracy: Around 50-51% - indicating little to no learning with our SGD optimizer and sigmoid activation.

🌐 Tanh Activation:¶

  • 📉 Test Loss: We see a that it slightly improves over epochs, ending at around 0.6916.
  • 📈 Test Accuracy: Peaks at 52.7%, showing marginal improvement compared to Sigmoid but still pretty limited learning capacity.

🚀 ReLU Activation:¶

  • 📉 Test Loss: Improves slightly but hovers near 0.6923-0.6928 range.
  • 📈 Test Accuracy: Peaks at 52.9%, performing slightly better than Sigmoid and Tanh!

💡 Key Insights:¶

🔑 General Observations:¶

  • Our SGD has a bit of a slower convergence and struggles to optimize in complex models without significant tuning. We see this in the learning rate adjustment - momentum).

📊 Limited Improvements with Activations:¶

  • All of our activation functions (Sigmoid, Tanh, ReLU) perform similarly with minimal variation, as demonstrated and tested above!
  • ReLU slightly edges out others in both accuracy and loss reduction.

⚠️ We do see a ~ Underfitting Issue ~¶

Our model is not learning meaningful patterns. I feel like this could most certainly be likely due to a couple factors:

  1. Shallow architecture?
  2. Lack of pre-trained embeddings and/or feature representation?
  3. Maybe small learning rates in SGD causing slow convergence ...

🔗 Next Steps to improve our model:¶

  1. We can try Adam with learning rate tuning!
  2. Then we can also consider adding deeper layers or using pre-trained embeddings.
  3. Experimenting w/ momentum or NAG for SGD could be a good direction to take this in.

from nltk.corpus import stopwords
import re

# going to try this method now and load some English stopwords ...
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))

# at this point we can update our clean_text function
def clean_text(text):
    text = re.sub(r'<.*?>', '', text)
    text = text.lower()
    text = re.sub(r'[^a-z\s]', '', text)
    text = ' '.join(word for word in text.split() if word not in stop_words)
    return text

df['review'] = df['review'].apply(clean_text)

GloVe Technique:¶

  • Using GloVe embeddings now, as they can be loaded using the gensim library! (reviewed in lecture!)

  • So here we are learning to load pre-trained GloVe embeddings, retrieve word vectors, and find words with similar meanings using those vectors. It's a great way to find representing words in a way that captures their semantic relationships!

In [81]:
# first we have to load out GloVe embeddings
embedding_index = {}
with open('glove.6B.100d.txt', encoding='utf-8') as f:
    for line in f:
        values = line.split()
        word = values[0]
        coeffs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
        embedding_index[word] = coeffs

# we follow by then creating embedding matrices ... 
embedding_dim = 100  
embedding_matrix = np.zeros((5000, embedding_dim))
for word, i in tokenizer.word_index.items():
    if i < 5000:
        embedding_vector = embedding_index.get(word)
        if embedding_vector is not None:
            embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector

model.add(Embedding(input_dim=5000, output_dim=embedding_dim, weights=[embedding_matrix], input_length=100, trainable=False))

def tokenize_text(data, max_length=100):
    return tokenizer(
        list(data),
        max_length=max_length,
        padding=True,
        truncation=True,
        return_tensors='tf'
    )

All PyTorch model weights were used when initializing TFBertForSequenceClassification.

Some weights or buffers of the TF 2.0 model TFBertForSequenceClassification were not initialized from the PyTorch model and are newly initialized: ['classifier.weight', 'classifier.bias']
You should probably TRAIN this model on a down-stream task to be able to use it for predictions and inference.
